political agents, Marie’s ballets also manipulated the subtle social and cultural codes of international courtly society in order to more deftly navigate rivalries and alliances both at home and abroad. At times the queen’s productions could challenge Henri IV’s immediate interests, contesting the influence enjoyed by his mistresses or giving space to implied critiques of official foreign policy, for example. Such defenses of Marie’s own position, though, took shape as part of a larger governmental program designed to promote the French consort queen’s political authority not in its own right but as a means of maintaining power for the new Bourbon monarchy in the event of Henri IV’s untimely death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aBalletzFrancexHistoryy17th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh  aBourbon monarchy.  aFrance.  aFrench court ballets.  aFrench.  aHenri IV.  aLouvre.  aQueen Marie de Médicis.  adance studies.  aliterary studies.  amusicology.  apolitical history.  awomen’s and gender studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751846240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487518462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487518462.jpg  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 English